“My name is Underworld,
And I reside in the dark.
For the paradox is
That I am the light hidden deep within your heart.

I am the wind upon your neck,
When you can’t see where to go. 
So Stop, Breathe & Listen,
I assure you, my love, it’s best to go slow.

There’s magic dancing in the air,
And it’s deeply profound. 
But you’ll never fucking feel it, see it or believe it
Unless you dig your grave deep deep deep 
Beneath the ground. 

Do not fear my love, 
It’s not disappearing that is hard.
It’s never having lived
Understanding what it’s like to have everything & nothing inside of your heart.

It stokes your fire to rage in a blaze,
And freezes the ice to chill your bones.
For it’s the duality,
The contrast necessary,
To sit in the darkness of the void & never feel alone

Be still, my love, 
It’s perfectly okay to be unsure.
For I assure you with sincerity,
That I will never leave you, not once
For I am your sword,
We will endure.

So go, with love, 
For that’s the essence of who you are.
And don’t you ever fucking forget

My name is Underworld,

India…Where to begin…

With the parts that incited a deep sorrow within my core ?

Or the moments with which I was overflowed with love & awe? 

Maybe it’s all love, after all. 

There’s primal aspects to life in second & third worlds, some more extreme than others. 

From the simplest measure as walking around with a wet ass that my charmin ultra pampered peach wasn’t accustomed to

To the depths of the Dhavari Slum, where workers breathe in microplastic laden air while creating the clothes on your back for pennies on the dollar. 

To kicking a bitter alpha monkey straight in his bitch ass jaw after he tried starting beef with me. 

To trusting a random man driving a tuk tuk like the Joker through unregulated, cow laden streets as you somehow avoid a certain death to get to your next destination

I met beautiful people working worlds away from their home, alone, to support their families. 

Children barefoot & dirty on the bustling streets alone selling tissues to afford a meal.

And Smells in the air that could rust copper in minutes. 

It’s places like India that don’t ask for your presence, they demand it. 

There’s no one to bitch or cry to when things don’t go your way, no lawyer to call when your car gets hit, and an ambulance that likely won’t make it to you in time if you get hurt. 

Most of these people don’t have 2 fucks to rub together about climate change, being misgendered or which Netflix comedy special was “offensive”. 

It’s a privilege to be afforded that level of thought while the majority can only think about their next meal. 

India is a lesson in what it means to stand in your power & maintain presence…a lesson many westerners desperately need to be smacked in the face with. 

And on a personal note, I found it interesting, if not uncomfortable, that in a sea of a billion+ people, I was a main attraction. 

Attracting the eyes & interest of what felt like every person I passed, being asked to take photos with 40+ strangers, simply for how I looked. 

Continued in comments ⬇️

Songkran 2023

It’s not every week that an entire country shuts down for 3 days & invites you to the biggest water gun fight since your 3rd grade birthday party. 🎉 

You see, this isn’t some random fiesta however. 

It’s the Thai New Year & it’s unlike any new year celebration you’ve experienced. 

There is no 60 second ball drop, no lip-synced performances, no elites watching from the comfort of their million dollar apartments & certainly no crappy overpriced drinks. 

It’s everyone from kids to store front owners to party goers and foreigners taking to the streets to wash away their sins & ring in the new year with good luck

….using buckets & buckets & buckets of spine chilling ice cold water 💦

When you step on the streets, you’re no longer in bangkok, but on a battleground. 

So you best be prepared with a waterproof bag & you’re supersoaker 5000 to fend off the free for all onslaught 🔫

I like to think its 95% good hearted fun & 5% devious vengeance…you know what I mean when you catch yourself smiling as you shoot an unsuspecting 5 year old directly in his grinning face 🔫 😜

And after hours of intoxicatingly walking around with puddle filled shoes & soaking random strangers, you find yourself warming up with a hot $2 bowl of soupy noodly goodness in the back of a neon lit tuk tuk, bumping funky thai beats & fending off the last remaining water attacks from fellow taxis like you’re in a game of Mario Kart. 🚗 

Songkran was…an unexpected introduction to Thailand, but a fortunate one to say the least. 

Not to mention, today is the first day of my “new year” & my first day without diarrhea in a week so…I’m feeling the luck already 🍀 

I’m learning more about this country, but I’ll save that for another post.

For now, take a moment to enjoy a glimpse at some of the beautiful people of Songkran…& when you see them, recognize they are you. 

They are your innocence, your playful child, your lust for life. 

And they are no different than you or me. 

Because we are one. 🖤

Peaceful Debauchery 🙏🏼😈

If I was asked to describe Thailand in 2 words, it would be that. 

A funky magical paradox. 💫 

A place where it’s normal, if not encouraged, to: 

- meditate at the most beautiful ancient buddhist temples in the morning,
- snorkel amongst stunning limestone formations in the day, 
- have a happy ending massage to relax in the afternoon 
- & have a night cap smoking a joint at one of the many bars, playing pool & eating a delicious bowl of pad thai

Maybe that’s how it got it’s name as The Land of Smiles. 😄

How could you not be happy with good weather, beautiful people, gorgeous views, delicious affordable food & all the deviant pleasures one could ask for….?

It’s Las Vegas on steroids but 40x better.

Yet, the thing that intrigues me the most in my travels, is always the people. 

You see the average Thai person works inspiringly hard to make just $300/month, yet nearly every person I pass won’t hesitate to share a smile & a bow with you.

No matter how long their day was

Mongolia 🇲🇳 

What comes to mind when you hear that word? 🧠 

Cold, distant, power, death…?

Prior to my visit, these are some thoughts that came to mind based on my little knowledge of the land of blue skies.

A 1000 year old empire that once was, Mongolia was built upon cunning leadership, resilience & death under the rule of Chinggis Khan…

Now today, a little-big nation of 3 million people, sandwiched in a corrupt stranglehold between the 2 largest eastern powers in the world, China & Russia. 💪🏽 

It is a land less travelled, likely due to its remoteness, lacking tourist infrastructure & the fact that its cold as f*ck in the winter. 

However, this enticed me to come. A nation founded upon nomadic herding culture, a practice still alive & thriving to this day, called to me as a current nomad myself. 🌍 

With some of the richest, unique history I’ve encountered, Mongolia is a definitive case study in power dynamics, resilience & community. 

Witnessing the abandoned structures from recent soviet rule to the preserved temples of an ancient past to the overwhelming amount of secondhand prius’s on the road, this is a culture that requires you to really inquire about what the f*ck happened & is happening here. 

Though a constrained, remote land craving for growth & connection, you can find a lot of life here. A Beautiful countryside. Growing families & Close connection amongst its people. 

In 9 days, I feel I’ve only scratched the surface. And in that time it’s people & beauty have already convinced me to stay longer. 

What I do know is I can only do my best to give back what Mongolia has so far given to me.

Nearly 10 months now on the road, saddled with nothing but 2 bags & a beating heart. 🖤

This time has taught me a thing or two that feels share-worthy:

1. Packing your life into 2 bags feels hard until you let go of what truly doesn’t serve you. Treat everything you own as sacred & let go of what isn’t. The weight & clutter you carry is holding you down. 

2. Anywhere can become home when you create a home within you. Your outside world is a representation of your inner world. Make it priority.

3. Be a beacon of love & your light will be felt everywhere you go. 

4. Drop your entitlement. It’s not attractive. 

5. Racism, corruption & shitty people are everywhere. Welcome to Earth.

6. If someone texts you back “555”, they are laughing, not having a stroke. 

7. 5-star hotels are cool, but sleeping on the ground in a local families home is cooler. 

8. Flexibility & patience are incredible skills. Stop trying to control everything.

On a personal note,

At moments I’ve felt deep gratitude for living out my dreams…

And at other times, I’ve felt the existential dread of my existence, questioning my abilities, decisions & direction.

That’s what happens when you take a road less traveled; you toe the line of genius & psychosis.

The past 2 years have been strange, beautiful, heart-wrenching & confusing all at once. 

I could have the nice house, car, wife, dog, baby & steady 6 figure salary now if I wanted. 

But what’s the fun in that when you can dive off the deep end into the abyss, creating an abstract life unique to you.

At times I loathe it, it’s been painful. But I know normalcy would kill me quicker. 

So I wake up daily and do what’s needed to not off myself, trusting it will all make sense in time. 

So let’s let the good times roll until the clock strikes midnight 🌙 

I love you 🖤
